_This issue has been moved from [a ticket on Developer Community](https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/content/idea/985091/suppress-obsolete-warnings-in-nameof.html)._

---
I suggest that you...

... suppress the obsolete warnings in C# nameof(..) statements (and in according statement of other .NET languages).

The reason for this request is, that nameof(<Obsolete Type>) or nameof(<Obsolete Member>) is often used in attributes and documentation to refere to the legacy object / member and then it must always be surrounded by 

#pragma warning disable CS0618
...
#pragma warning restore CS0618

(or added to the GlobalSuppression file).

As I do not see any benefit of nameof(...) displaying Obsolete warnings I suggest to suppress them generally in that situation.

Example that displayes warnings:

```
  [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.All, Inherited = false, AllowMultiple = true)]
    public class ReplacementAttribute : Attribute {

public ReplacementAttribute(string message) {
            Message = message;
        }

public string Message { get; private set; }

}

[Obsolete("Does not support XYZ! Use class '" + nameof(ReplacementObject) + "' instead.")]
    public class LegacyObject { 

//Some members

}

[Replacement("Does support XYZ! Replacement class for '" + nameof(LegacyObject) + "'.")]
    public class ReplacementObject {

//Some members

}

public static class ReplacementObjectExtensions {

[Obsolete("Does not support XYZ! Concerns the returned '" + nameof(LegacyObject) + "' object.")]
        public static LegacyObject ConvertToLegacy(ReplacementObject currentVersion) {
            LegacyObject result = new LegacyObject();
            //Fill in properties
            return result;
        }

[Obsolete("Does not support XYZ! Concerns the given '" + nameof(LegacyObject) + "' object.")]
        public static ReplacementObject ConvertToLegacy(LegacyObject currentVersion) {
            ReplacementObject result = new ReplacementObject();
            //Fill in properties
            return result;
        }

}
```

Example that suppresses them with #pragma:

```
    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.All, Inherited = false, AllowMultiple = true)]
    public class ReplacementAttribute : Attribute {

public ReplacementAttribute(string message) {
            Message = message;
        }

public string Message { get; private set; }

}

[Obsolete("Does not support XYZ! Use class '" + nameof(ReplacementObject) + "' instead.")]
    public class LegacyObject { 

//Some members

}

#pragma warning disable CS0618 // Type or member is obsolete
    [Replacement("Does support XYZ! Replacement class for '" + nameof(LegacyObject) + "'.")]
#pragma warning restore CS0618 // Type or member is obsolete
    public class ReplacementObject {

//Some members

}

public static class ReplacementObjectExtensions {

#pragma warning disable CS0618 // Type or member is obsolete
        [Obsolete("Does not support XYZ! Concerns the returned '" + nameof(LegacyObject) + "' object.")]
#pragma warning restore CS0618 // Type or member is obsolete
        public static LegacyObject ConvertToLegacy(ReplacementObject currentVersion) {
            LegacyObject result = new LegacyObject();
            //Fill in properties
            return result;
        }

#pragma warning disable CS0618 // Type or member is obsolete
        [Obsolete("Does not support XYZ! Concerns the given '" + nameof(LegacyObject) + "' object.")]
#pragma warning restore CS0618 // Type or member is obsolete
        public static ReplacementObject ConvertToLegacy(LegacyObject currentVersion) {
            ReplacementObject result = new ReplacementObject();
            //Fill in properties
            return result;
        }

}

```

Best regards
Chris

